132 def get_fernet():
133  """
134  Deferred load of Fernet key.
135 
136  This function could fail either because Cryptography is not installed
137  or because the Fernet key is invalid.
138 
139  :return: Fernet object
140  :raises: AirflowException if there's a problem trying to load Fernet
141  """
142  global _fernet
143  if _fernet:
144  return _fernet
145  try:
146  from cryptography.fernet import Fernet, InvalidToken
147  global InvalidFernetToken
148  InvalidFernetToken = InvalidToken
149 
150  except BuiltinImportError:
151  LoggingMixin().log.warn("cryptography not found - values will not be stored "
152  "encrypted.",
153  exc_info=1)
154  _fernet = NullFernet()
155  return _fernet
156 
157  try:
158  _fernet = Fernet(configuration.conf.get('core', 'FERNET_KEY').encode('utf-8'))
159  _fernet.is_encrypted = True
160  return _fernet
161  except (ValueError, TypeError) as ve:
162  raise AirflowException("Could not create Fernet object: {}".format(ve))

169 def clear_task_instances(tis,
170  session,
171  activate_dag_runs=True,
172  dag=None,
173  ):
174  """
175  Clears a set of task instances, but makes sure the running ones
176  get killed.
177 
178  :param tis: a list of task instances
179  :param session: current session
180  :param activate_dag_runs: flag to check for active dag run
181  :param dag: DAG object
182  """
183  job_ids = []
184  for ti in tis:
185  if ti.state == State.RUNNING:
186  if ti.job_id:
187  ti.state = State.SHUTDOWN
188  job_ids.append(ti.job_id)
189  else:
190  task_id = ti.task_id
191  if dag and dag.has_task(task_id):
192  task = dag.get_task(task_id)
193  task_retries = task.retries
194  ti.max_tries = ti.try_number + task_retries - 1
195  else:
196  # Ignore errors when updating max_tries if dag is None or
197  # task not found in dag since database records could be
198  # outdated. We make max_tries the maximum value of its
199  # original max_tries or the current task try number.
200  ti.max_tries = max(ti.max_tries, ti.try_number - 1)
201  ti.state = State.NONE
202  session.merge(ti)
203 
204  if job_ids:
205  from airflow.jobs import BaseJob as BJ
206  for job in session.query(BJ).filter(BJ.id.in_(job_ids)).all():
207  job.state = State.SHUTDOWN
208 
209  if activate_dag_runs and tis:
210  drs = session.query(DagRun).filter(
211  DagRun.dag_id.in_({ti.dag_id for ti in tis}),
212  DagRun.execution_date.in_({ti.execution_date for ti in tis}),
213  ).all()
214  for dr in drs:
215  dr.state = State.RUNNING
216  dr.start_date = timezone.utcnow()

219 class DagBag(BaseDagBag, LoggingMixin):
220  """
221  A dagbag is a collection of dags, parsed out of a folder tree and has high
222  level configuration settings, like what database to use as a backend and
223  what executor to use to fire off tasks. This makes it easier to run
224  distinct environments for say production and development, tests, or for
225  different teams or security profiles. What would have been system level
226  settings are now dagbag level so that one system can run multiple,
227  independent settings sets.
228 
229  :param dag_folder: the folder to scan to find DAGs
230  :type dag_folder: unicode
231  :param executor: the executor to use when executing task instances
232  in this DagBag
233  :param include_examples: whether to include the examples that ship
234  with airflow or not
235  :type include_examples: bool
236  :param has_logged: an instance boolean that gets flipped from False to True after a
237  file has been skipped. This is to prevent overloading the user with logging
238  messages about skipped files. Therefore only once per DagBag is a file logged
239  being skipped.
240  """
241 
242  # static class variables to detetct dag cycle
243  CYCLE_NEW = 0
244  CYCLE_IN_PROGRESS = 1
245  CYCLE_DONE = 2
246 
247  def __init__(
248  self,
249  dag_folder=None,
250  executor=None,
251  include_examples=configuration.conf.getboolean('core', 'LOAD_EXAMPLES')):
252 
253  # do not use default arg in signature, to fix import cycle on plugin load
254  if executor is None:
255  executor = GetDefaultExecutor()
256  dag_folder = dag_folder or settings.DAGS_FOLDER
257  self.log.info("Filling up the DagBag from %s", dag_folder)
258  self.dag_folder = dag_folder
259  self.dags = {}
260  # the file's last modified timestamp when we last read it
261  self.file_last_changed = {}
262  self.executor = executor
263  self.import_errors = {}
264  self.has_logged = False
265 
266  if include_examples:
267  example_dag_folder = os.path.join(
268  os.path.dirname(__file__),
269  'example_dags')
270  self.collect_dags(example_dag_folder)
271  self.collect_dags(dag_folder)

279  def get_dag(self, dag_id):
280  """
281  Gets the DAG out of the dictionary, and refreshes it if expired
282  """
283  # If asking for a known subdag, we want to refresh the parent
284  root_dag_id = dag_id
285  if dag_id in self.dags:
286  dag = self.dags[dag_id]
287  if dag.is_subdag:
288  root_dag_id = dag.parent_dag.dag_id
289 
290  # If the dag corresponding to root_dag_id is absent or expired
291  orm_dag = DagModel.get_current(root_dag_id)
292  if orm_dag and (
293  root_dag_id not in self.dags or
294  (
295  orm_dag.last_expired and
296  dag.last_loaded < orm_dag.last_expired
297  )
298  ):
299  # Reprocess source file
300  found_dags = self.process_file(
301  filepath=orm_dag.fileloc, only_if_updated=False)
302 
303  # If the source file no longer exports `dag_id`, delete it from self.dags
304  if found_dags and dag_id in [found_dag.dag_id for found_dag in found_dags]:
305  return self.dags[dag_id]
306  elif dag_id in self.dags:
307  del self.dags[dag_id]
308  return self.dags.get(dag_id)

310  def process_file(self, filepath, only_if_updated=True, safe_mode=True):
311  """
312  Given a path to a python module or zip file, this method imports
313  the module and look for dag objects within it.
314  """
315  found_dags = []
316 
317  # if the source file no longer exists in the DB or in the filesystem,
318  # return an empty list
319  # todo: raise exception?
320  if filepath is None or not os.path.isfile(filepath):
321  return found_dags
322 
323  try:
324  # This failed before in what may have been a git sync
325  # race condition
326  file_last_changed_on_disk = datetime.fromtimestamp(os.path.getmtime(filepath))
327  if only_if_updated \
328  and filepath in self.file_last_changed \
329  and file_last_changed_on_disk == self.file_last_changed[filepath]:
330  return found_dags
331 
332  except Exception as e:
333  self.log.exception(e)
334  return found_dags
335 
336  mods = []
337  if not zipfile.is_zipfile(filepath):
338  if safe_mode and os.path.isfile(filepath):
339  with open(filepath, 'rb') as f:
340  content = f.read()
341  if not all([s in content for s in (b'DAG', b'airflow')]):
342  self.file_last_changed[filepath] = file_last_changed_on_disk
343  # Don't want to spam user with skip messages
344  if not self.has_logged:
345  self.has_logged = True
346  self.log.info(
347  "File %s assumed to contain no DAGs. Skipping.",
348  filepath)
349  return found_dags
350 
351  self.log.debug("Importing %s", filepath)
352  org_mod_name, _ = os.path.splitext(os.path.split(filepath)[-1])
353  mod_name = ('unusual_prefix_' +
354  hashlib.sha1(filepath.encode('utf-8')).hexdigest() +
355  '_' + org_mod_name)
356 
357  if mod_name in sys.modules:
358  del sys.modules[mod_name]
359 
360  with timeout(configuration.conf.getint('core', "DAGBAG_IMPORT_TIMEOUT")):
361  try:
362  m = imp.load_source(mod_name, filepath)
363  mods.append(m)
364  except Exception as e:
365  self.log.exception("Failed to import: %s", filepath)
366  self.import_errors[filepath] = str(e)
367  self.file_last_changed[filepath] = file_last_changed_on_disk
368 
369  else:
370  zip_file = zipfile.ZipFile(filepath)
371  for mod in zip_file.infolist():
372  head, _ = os.path.split(mod.filename)
373  mod_name, ext = os.path.splitext(mod.filename)
374  if not head and (ext == '.py' or ext == '.pyc'):
375  if mod_name == '__init__':
376  self.log.warning("Found __init__.%s at root of %s", ext, filepath)
377  if safe_mode:
378  with zip_file.open(mod.filename) as zf:
379  self.log.debug("Reading %s from %s", mod.filename, filepath)
380  content = zf.read()
381  if not all([s in content for s in (b'DAG', b'airflow')]):
382  self.file_last_changed[filepath] = (
383  file_last_changed_on_disk)
384  # todo: create ignore list
385  # Don't want to spam user with skip messages
386  if not self.has_logged:
387  self.has_logged = True
388  self.log.info(
389  "File %s assumed to contain no DAGs. Skipping.",
390  filepath)
391 
392  if mod_name in sys.modules:
393  del sys.modules[mod_name]
394 
395  try:
396  sys.path.insert(0, filepath)
397  m = importlib.import_module(mod_name)
398  mods.append(m)
399  except Exception as e:
400  self.log.exception("Failed to import: %s", filepath)
401  self.import_errors[filepath] = str(e)
402  self.file_last_changed[filepath] = file_last_changed_on_disk
403 
404  for m in mods:
405  for dag in list(m.__dict__.values()):
406  if isinstance(dag, DAG):
407  if not dag.full_filepath:
408  dag.full_filepath = filepath
409  if dag.fileloc != filepath:
410  dag.fileloc = filepath
411  try:
412  dag.is_subdag = False
413  self.bag_dag(dag, parent_dag=dag, root_dag=dag)
414  found_dags.append(dag)
415  found_dags += dag.subdags
416  except AirflowDagCycleException as cycle_exception:
417  self.log.exception("Failed to bag_dag: %s", dag.full_filepath)
418  self.import_errors[dag.full_filepath] = str(cycle_exception)
419  self.file_last_changed[dag.full_filepath] = \
420  file_last_changed_on_disk
421 
422  self.file_last_changed[filepath] = file_last_changed_on_disk
423  return found_dags

425  @provide_session
426  def kill_zombies(self, session=None):
427  """
428  Fails tasks that haven't had a heartbeat in too long
429  """
430  from airflow.jobs import LocalTaskJob as LJ
431  self.log.info("Finding 'running' jobs without a recent heartbeat")
432  TI = TaskInstance
433  secs = configuration.conf.getint('scheduler', 'scheduler_zombie_task_threshold')
434  limit_dttm = timezone.utcnow() - timedelta(seconds=secs)
435  self.log.info("Failing jobs without heartbeat after %s", limit_dttm)
436 
437  tis = (
438  session.query(TI)
439  .join(LJ, TI.job_id == LJ.id)
440  .filter(TI.state == State.RUNNING)
441  .filter(
442  or_(
443  LJ.state != State.RUNNING,
444  LJ.latest_heartbeat < limit_dttm,
445  ))
446  .all()
447  )
448 
449  for ti in tis:
450  if ti and ti.dag_id in self.dags:
451  dag = self.dags[ti.dag_id]
452  if ti.task_id in dag.task_ids:
453  task = dag.get_task(ti.task_id)
454 
455  # now set non db backed vars on ti
456  ti.task = task
457  ti.test_mode = configuration.getboolean('core', 'unit_test_mode')
458 
459  ti.handle_failure("{} detected as zombie".format(ti),
460  ti.test_mode, ti.get_template_context())
461  self.log.info(
462  'Marked zombie job %s as %s', ti, ti.state)
463  Stats.incr('zombies_killed')
464  session.commit()

466  def bag_dag(self, dag, parent_dag, root_dag):
467  """
468  Adds the DAG into the bag, recurses into sub dags.
469  Throws AirflowDagCycleException if a cycle is detected in this dag or its subdags
470  """
471 
472  dag.test_cycle() # throws if a task cycle is found
473 
474  dag.resolve_template_files()
475  dag.last_loaded = timezone.utcnow()
476 
477  for task in dag.tasks:
478  settings.policy(task)
479 
480  subdags = dag.subdags
481 
482  try:
483  for subdag in subdags:
484  subdag.full_filepath = dag.full_filepath
485  subdag.parent_dag = dag
486  subdag.is_subdag = True
487  self.bag_dag(subdag, parent_dag=dag, root_dag=root_dag)
488 
489  self.dags[dag.dag_id] = dag
490  self.log.debug('Loaded DAG {dag}'.format(**locals()))
491  except AirflowDagCycleException as cycle_exception:
492  # There was an error in bagging the dag. Remove it from the list of dags
493  self.log.exception('Exception bagging dag: {dag.dag_id}'.format(**locals()))
494  # Only necessary at the root level since DAG.subdags automatically
495  # performs DFS to search through all subdags
496  if dag == root_dag:
497  for subdag in subdags:
498  if subdag.dag_id in self.dags:
499  del self.dags[subdag.dag_id]
500  raise cycle_exception

502  def collect_dags(
503  self,
504  dag_folder=None,
505  only_if_updated=True):
506  """
507  Given a file path or a folder, this method looks for python modules,
508  imports them and adds them to the dagbag collection.
509 
510  Note that if a .airflowignore file is found while processing,
511  the directory, it will behaves much like a .gitignore does,
512  ignoring files that match any of the regex patterns specified
513  in the file. **Note**: The patterns in .airflowignore are treated as
514  un-anchored regexes, not shell-like glob patterns.
515  """
516  start_dttm = timezone.utcnow()
517  dag_folder = dag_folder or self.dag_folder
518 
519  # Used to store stats around DagBag processing
520  stats = []
521  FileLoadStat = namedtuple(
522  'FileLoadStat', "file duration dag_num task_num dags")
523  for filepath in utils.dag_processing.list_py_file_paths(dag_folder):
524  try:
525  ts = timezone.utcnow()
526  found_dags = self.process_file(
527  filepath, only_if_updated=only_if_updated)
528 
529  td = timezone.utcnow() - ts
530  td = td.total_seconds() + (
531  float(td.microseconds) / 1000000)
532  stats.append(FileLoadStat(
533  filepath.replace(dag_folder, ''),
534  td,
535  len(found_dags),
536  sum([len(dag.tasks) for dag in found_dags]),
537  str([dag.dag_id for dag in found_dags]),
538  ))
539  except Exception as e:
540  self.log.exception(e)
541  Stats.gauge(
542  'collect_dags', (timezone.utcnow() - start_dttm).total_seconds(), 1)
543  Stats.gauge(
544  'dagbag_size', len(self.dags), 1)
545  Stats.gauge(
546  'dagbag_import_errors', len(self.import_errors), 1)
547  self.dagbag_stats = sorted(
548  stats, key=lambda x: x.duration, reverse=True)
549 
550  def dagbag_report(self):
551  """Prints a report around DagBag loading stats"""
552  report = textwrap.dedent("""\n
553  -------------------------------------------------------------------
554  DagBag loading stats for {dag_folder}
555  -------------------------------------------------------------------
556  Number of DAGs: {dag_num}
557  Total task number: {task_num}
558  DagBag parsing time: {duration}
559  {table}
560  """)
561  stats = self.dagbag_stats
562  return report.format(
563  dag_folder=self.dag_folder,
564  duration=sum([o.duration for o in stats]),
565  dag_num=sum([o.dag_num for o in stats]),
566  task_num=sum([o.task_num for o in stats]),
567  table=pprinttable(stats),
568  )

678  def parse_from_uri(self, uri):
679  temp_uri = urlparse(uri)
680  hostname = temp_uri.hostname or ''
681  if '%2f' in hostname:
682  hostname = hostname.replace('%2f', '/').replace('%2F', '/')
683  conn_type = temp_uri.scheme
684  if conn_type == 'postgresql':
685  conn_type = 'postgres'
686  self.conn_type = conn_type
687  self.host = hostname
688  self.schema = temp_uri.path[1:]
689  self.login = temp_uri.username
690  self.password = temp_uri.password
691  self.port = temp_uri.port
692  if temp_uri.query:
693  self.extra = json.dumps(dict(parse_qsl(temp_uri.query)))

818 class DagPickle(Base):
819  """
820  Dags can originate from different places (user repos, master repo, ...)
821  and also get executed in different places (different executors). This
822  object represents a version of a DAG and becomes a source of truth for
823  a BackfillJob execution. A pickle is a native python serialized object,
824  and in this case gets stored in the database for the duration of the job.

827  the database.
828  """

834  __tablename__ = "dag_pickle"
835

837  self.dag_id = dag.dag_id
838  if hasattr(dag, 'template_env'):
839  dag.template_env = None
840  self.pickle_hash = hash(dag)
841  self.pickle = dag

844 class TaskInstance(Base, LoggingMixin):

846  Task instances store the state of a task instance. This table is the
847  authority and single source of truth around what tasks have run and the
848  state they are in.
849 
850  The SqlAlchemy model doesn't have a SqlAlchemy foreign key to the task or
851  dag model deliberately to have more control over transactions.
852 
853  Database transactions on this table should insure double triggers and
854  any confusion around what task instances are or aren't ready to run
855  even while multiple schedulers may be firing task instances.
856  """

1027  @staticmethod
1028  def generate_command(dag_id,
1029  task_id,
1030  execution_date,
1031  mark_success=False,
1032  ignore_all_deps=False,
1033  ignore_depends_on_past=False,
1034  ignore_task_deps=False,
1035  ignore_ti_state=False,
1036  local=False,
1037  pickle_id=None,
1038  file_path=None,
1039  raw=False,
1040  job_id=None,
1041  pool=None,
1042  cfg_path=None
1043  ):
1044  """
1045  Generates the shell command required to execute this task instance.
1046 
1047  :param dag_id: DAG ID
1048  :type dag_id: unicode
1049  :param task_id: Task ID
1050  :type task_id: unicode
1051  :param execution_date: Execution date for the task
1052  :type execution_date: datetime
1053  :param mark_success: Whether to mark the task as successful
1054  :type mark_success: bool
1055  :param ignore_all_deps: Ignore all ignorable dependencies.
1056  Overrides the other ignore_* parameters.
1057  :type ignore_all_deps: boolean
1058  :param ignore_depends_on_past: Ignore depends_on_past parameter of DAGs
1059  (e.g. for Backfills)
1060  :type ignore_depends_on_past: boolean
1061  :param ignore_task_deps: Ignore task-specific dependencies such as depends_on_past
1062  and trigger rule
1063  :type ignore_task_deps: boolean
1064  :param ignore_ti_state: Ignore the task instance's previous failure/success
1065  :type ignore_ti_state: boolean
1066  :param local: Whether to run the task locally
1067  :type local: bool
1068  :param pickle_id: If the DAG was serialized to the DB, the ID
1069  associated with the pickled DAG
1070  :type pickle_id: unicode
1071  :param file_path: path to the file containing the DAG definition
1072  :param raw: raw mode (needs more details)
1073  :param job_id: job ID (needs more details)
1074  :param pool: the Airflow pool that the task should run in
1075  :type pool: unicode
1076  :param cfg_path: the Path to the configuration file
1077  :type cfg_path: basestring
1078  :return: shell command that can be used to run the task instance
1079  """
1080  iso = execution_date.isoformat()
1081  cmd = ["airflow", "run", str(dag_id), str(task_id), str(iso)]
1082  cmd.extend(["--mark_success"]) if mark_success else None
1083  cmd.extend(["--pickle", str(pickle_id)]) if pickle_id else None
1084  cmd.extend(["--job_id", str(job_id)]) if job_id else None
1085  cmd.extend(["-A"]) if ignore_all_deps else None
1086  cmd.extend(["-i"]) if ignore_task_deps else None
1087  cmd.extend(["-I"]) if ignore_depends_on_past else None
1088  cmd.extend(["--force"]) if ignore_ti_state else None
1089  cmd.extend(["--local"]) if local else None
1090  cmd.extend(["--pool", pool]) if pool else None
1091  cmd.extend(["--raw"]) if raw else None
1092  cmd.extend(["-sd", file_path]) if file_path else None
1093  cmd.extend(["--cfg_path", cfg_path]) if cfg_path else None
1094  return cmd

1174  @provide_session
1175  def refresh_from_db(self, session=None, lock_for_update=False):
1176  """
1177  Refreshes the task instance from the database based on the primary key
1178 
1179  :param lock_for_update: if True, indicates that the database should
1180  lock the TaskInstance (issuing a FOR UPDATE clause) until the
1181  session is committed.
1182  """
1183  TI = TaskInstance
1184

1186  TI.dag_id == self.dag_id,

1188  TI.execution_date == self.execution_date)
1189 
1190  if lock_for_update:
1191  ti = qry.with_for_update().first()
1192  else:
1193  ti = qry.first()
1194  if ti:
1195  self.state = ti.state
1196  self.start_date = ti.start_date
1197  self.end_date = ti.end_date
1198  # Get the raw value of try_number column, don't read through the
1199  # accessor here otherwise it will be incremeneted by one already.
1200  self.try_number = ti._try_number
1201  self.max_tries = ti.max_tries
1202  self.hostname = ti.hostname
1203  self.pid = ti.pid
1204  self.executor_config = ti.executor_config
1205  else:
1206  self.state = None

1244  @provide_session
1245  def are_dependents_done(self, session=None):
1246  """
1247  Checks whether the dependents of this task instance have all succeeded.
1248  This is meant to be used by wait_for_downstream.
1249 
1250  This is useful when you do not want to start processing the next
1251  schedule of a task until the dependents are done. For instance,
1252  if the task DROPs and recreates a table.
1253  """
1254  task = self.task
1255 
1256  if not task.downstream_task_ids:
1257  return True
1258 
1259  ti = session.query(func.count(TaskInstance.task_id)).filter(
1260  TaskInstance.dag_id == self.dag_id,
1261  TaskInstance.task_id.in_(task.downstream_task_ids),
1262  TaskInstance.execution_date == self.execution_date,

1298  @provide_session
1299  def are_dependencies_met(
1300  self,
1301  dep_context=None,
1302  session=None,
1303  verbose=False):
1304  """
1305  Returns whether or not all the conditions are met for this task instance to be run
1306  given the context for the dependencies (e.g. a task instance being force run from
1307  the UI will ignore some dependencies).
1308 
1309  :param dep_context: The execution context that determines the dependencies that
1310  should be evaluated.
1311  :type dep_context: DepContext
1312  :param session: database session
1313  :type session: Session
1314  :param verbose: whether log details on failed dependencies on
1315  info or debug log level
1316  :type verbose: boolean
1317  """
1318  dep_context = dep_context or DepContext()
1319  failed = False
1320  verbose_aware_logger = self.log.info if verbose else self.log.debug
1321  for dep_status in self.get_failed_dep_statuses(
1322  dep_context=dep_context,
1323  session=session):
1324  failed = True
1325 
1326  verbose_aware_logger(
1327  "Dependencies not met for %s, dependency '%s' FAILED: %s",
1328  self, dep_status.dep_name, dep_status.reason
1329  )
1330 
1331  if failed:
1332  return False
1333 
1334  verbose_aware_logger("Dependencies all met for %s", self)
1335  return True

1339  self,

1341  session=None):

1363  def next_retry_datetime(self):
1364  """
1365  Get datetime of the next retry if the task instance fails. For exponential
1366  backoff, retry_delay is used as base and will be converted to seconds.
1367  """
1368  delay = self.task.retry_delay
1369  if self.task.retry_exponential_backoff:
1370  min_backoff = int(delay.total_seconds() * (2 ** (self.try_number - 2)))
1371  # deterministic per task instance
1372  hash = int(hashlib.sha1("{}#{}#{}#{}".format(self.dag_id,
1373  self.task_id,
1374  self.execution_date,
1375  self.try_number)
1376  .encode('utf-8')).hexdigest(), 16)
1377  # between 0.5 * delay * (2^retry_number) and 1.0 * delay * (2^retry_number)
1378  modded_hash = min_backoff + hash % min_backoff
1379  # timedelta has a maximum representable value. The exponentiation
1380  # here means this value can be exceeded after a certain number
1381  # of tries (around 50 if the initial delay is 1s, even fewer if
1382  # the delay is larger). Cap the value here before creating a
1383  # timedelta object so the operation doesn't fail.
1384  delay_backoff_in_seconds = min(
1385  modded_hash,
1386  timedelta.max.total_seconds() - 1
1387  )
1388  delay = timedelta(seconds=delay_backoff_in_seconds)
1389  if self.task.max_retry_delay:
1390  delay = min(self.task.max_retry_delay, delay)
1391  return self.end_date + delay

1399  self.next_retry_datetime() < timezone.utcnow())

1437  @provide_session
1438  def _check_and_change_state_before_execution(
1439  self,
1440  verbose=True,
1441  ignore_all_deps=False,
1442  ignore_depends_on_past=False,
1443  ignore_task_deps=False,
1444  ignore_ti_state=False,
1445  mark_success=False,
1446  test_mode=False,
1447  job_id=None,
1448  pool=None,
1449  session=None):
1450  """
1451  Checks dependencies and then sets state to RUNNING if they are met. Returns
1452  True if and only if state is set to RUNNING, which implies that task should be
1453  executed, in preparation for _run_raw_task
1454 
1455  :param verbose: whether to turn on more verbose logging
1456  :type verbose: boolean
1457  :param ignore_all_deps: Ignore all of the non-critical dependencies, just runs
1458  :type ignore_all_deps: boolean
1459  :param ignore_depends_on_past: Ignore depends_on_past DAG attribute
1460  :type ignore_depends_on_past: boolean
1461  :param ignore_task_deps: Don't check the dependencies of this TI's task
1462  :type ignore_task_deps: boolean
1463  :param ignore_ti_state: Disregards previous task instance state
1464  :type ignore_ti_state: boolean
1465  :param mark_success: Don't run the task, mark its state as success
1466  :type mark_success: boolean
1467  :param test_mode: Doesn't record success or failure in the DB
1468  :type test_mode: boolean
1469  :param pool: specifies the pool to use to run the task instance
1470  :type pool: str
1471  :return: whether the state was changed to running or not
1472  :rtype: bool
1473  """
1474  task = self.task
1475  self.pool = pool or task.pool
1476  self.test_mode = test_mode
1477  self.refresh_from_db(session=session, lock_for_update=True)
1478  self.job_id = job_id
1479  self.hostname = get_hostname()
1480  self.operator = task.__class__.__name__
1481 
1482  if not ignore_all_deps and not ignore_ti_state and self.state == State.SUCCESS:
1483  Stats.incr('previously_succeeded', 1, 1)
1484 
1485  queue_dep_context = DepContext(
1486  deps=QUEUE_DEPS,
1487  ignore_all_deps=ignore_all_deps,
1488  ignore_ti_state=ignore_ti_state,
1489  ignore_depends_on_past=ignore_depends_on_past,
1490  ignore_task_deps=ignore_task_deps)
1491  if not self.are_dependencies_met(
1492  dep_context=queue_dep_context,
1493  session=session,
1494  verbose=True):
1495  session.commit()
1496  return False
1497 
1498  # TODO: Logging needs cleanup, not clear what is being printed
1499  hr = "\n" + ("-" * 80) + "\n" # Line break
1500 
1501  # For reporting purposes, we report based on 1-indexed,
1502  # not 0-indexed lists (i.e. Attempt 1 instead of
1503  # Attempt 0 for the first attempt).
1504  msg = "Starting attempt {attempt} of {total}".format(
1505  attempt=self.try_number,
1506  total=self.max_tries + 1)
1507  self.start_date = timezone.utcnow()
1508 
1509  dep_context = DepContext(
1510  deps=RUN_DEPS - QUEUE_DEPS,
1511  ignore_all_deps=ignore_all_deps,
1512  ignore_depends_on_past=ignore_depends_on_past,
1513  ignore_task_deps=ignore_task_deps,
1514  ignore_ti_state=ignore_ti_state)
1515  runnable = self.are_dependencies_met(
1516  dep_context=dep_context,
1517  session=session,
1518  verbose=True)
1519 
1520  if not runnable and not mark_success:
1521  # FIXME: we might have hit concurrency limits, which means we probably
1522  # have been running prematurely. This should be handled in the
1523  # scheduling mechanism.
1524  self.state = State.NONE
1525  msg = ("FIXME: Rescheduling due to concurrency limits reached at task "
1526  "runtime. Attempt {attempt} of {total}. State set to NONE.").format(
1527  attempt=self.try_number,
1528  total=self.max_tries + 1)
1529  self.log.warning(hr + msg + hr)
1530 
1531  self.queued_dttm = timezone.utcnow()
1532  self.log.info("Queuing into pool %s", self.pool)
1533  session.merge(self)
1534  session.commit()
1535  return False
1536 
1537  # Another worker might have started running this task instance while
1538  # the current worker process was blocked on refresh_from_db
1539  if self.state == State.RUNNING:
1540  msg = "Task Instance already running {}".format(self)
1541  self.log.warning(msg)
1542  session.commit()
1543  return False
1544 
1545  # print status message
1546  self.log.info(hr + msg + hr)
1547  self._try_number += 1
1548 
1549  if not test_mode:
1550  session.add(Log(State.RUNNING, self))
1551  self.state = State.RUNNING
1552  self.pid = os.getpid()
1553  self.end_date = None
1554  if not test_mode:
1555  session.merge(self)
1556  session.commit()
1557 
1558  # Closing all pooled connections to prevent
1559  # "max number of connections reached"
1560  settings.engine.dispose()
1561  if verbose:
1562  if mark_success:
1563  msg = "Marking success for {} on {}".format(self.task,
1564  self.execution_date)
1565  self.log.info(msg)
1566  else:
1567  msg = "Executing {} on {}".format(self.task, self.execution_date)
1568  self.log.info(msg)
1569  return True

1571  @provide_session
1572  def _run_raw_task(
1573  self,
1574  mark_success=False,
1575  test_mode=False,
1576  job_id=None,
1577  pool=None,
1578  session=None):
1579  """
1580  Immediately runs the task (without checking or changing db state
1581  before execution) and then sets the appropriate final state after
1582  completion and runs any post-execute callbacks. Meant to be called
1583  only after another function changes the state to running.
1584 
1585  :param mark_success: Don't run the task, mark its state as success
1586  :type mark_success: boolean
1587  :param test_mode: Doesn't record success or failure in the DB
1588  :type test_mode: boolean
1589  :param pool: specifies the pool to use to run the task instance
1590  :type pool: str
1591  """
1592  task = self.task
1593  self.pool = pool or task.pool
1594  self.test_mode = test_mode
1595  self.refresh_from_db(session=session)
1596  self.job_id = job_id
1597  self.hostname = get_hostname()
1598  self.operator = task.__class__.__name__
1599 
1600  context = {}
1601  try:
1602  if not mark_success:
1603  context = self.get_template_context()
1604 
1605  task_copy = copy.copy(task)
1606  self.task = task_copy
1607 
1608  def signal_handler(signum, frame):
1609  self.log.error("Received SIGTERM. Terminating subprocesses.")
1610  task_copy.on_kill()
1611  raise AirflowException("Task received SIGTERM signal")
1612  signal.signal(signal.SIGTERM, signal_handler)
1613 
1614  # Don't clear Xcom until the task is certain to execute
1615  self.clear_xcom_data()
1616 
1617  self.render_templates()
1618  task_copy.pre_execute(context=context)
1619 
1620  # If a timeout is specified for the task, make it fail
1621  # if it goes beyond
1622  result = None
1623  if task_copy.execution_timeout:
1624  try:
1625  with timeout(int(
1626  task_copy.execution_timeout.total_seconds())):
1627  result = task_copy.execute(context=context)
1628  except AirflowTaskTimeout:
1629  task_copy.on_kill()
1630  raise
1631  else:
1632  result = task_copy.execute(context=context)
1633 
1634  # If the task returns a result, push an XCom containing it
1635  if result is not None:
1636  self.xcom_push(key=XCOM_RETURN_KEY, value=result)
1637 
1638  # TODO remove deprecated behavior in Airflow 2.0
1639  try:
1640  task_copy.post_execute(context=context, result=result)
1641  except TypeError as e:
1642  if 'unexpected keyword argument' in str(e):
1643  warnings.warn(
1644  'BaseOperator.post_execute() now takes two '
1645  'arguments, `context` and `result`, but "{}" only '
1646  'expected one. This behavior is deprecated and '
1647  'will be removed in a future version of '
1648  'Airflow.'.format(self.task_id),
1649  category=DeprecationWarning)
1650  task_copy.post_execute(context=context)
1651  else:
1652  raise
1653 
1654  Stats.incr('operator_successes_{}'.format(
1655  self.task.__class__.__name__), 1, 1)
1656  Stats.incr('ti_successes')
1657  self.refresh_from_db(lock_for_update=True)
1658  self.state = State.SUCCESS
1659  except AirflowSkipException:
1660  self.refresh_from_db(lock_for_update=True)
1661  self.state = State.SKIPPED
1662  except AirflowException as e:
1663  self.refresh_from_db()
1664  # for case when task is marked as success externally
1665  # current behavior doesn't hit the success callback
1666  if self.state == State.SUCCESS:
1667  return
1668  else:
1669  self.handle_failure(e, test_mode, context)
1670  raise
1671  except (Exception, KeyboardInterrupt) as e:
1672  self.handle_failure(e, test_mode, context)
1673  raise
1674 
1675  # Recording SUCCESS
1676  self.end_date = timezone.utcnow()
1677  self.set_duration()
1678  if not test_mode:
1679  session.add(Log(self.state, self))
1680  session.merge(self)
1681  session.commit()
1682 
1683  # Success callback
1684  try:
1685  if task.on_success_callback:
1686  task.on_success_callback(context)
1687  except Exception as e3:
1688  self.log.error("Failed when executing success callback")
1689  self.log.exception(e3)
1690 
1691  session.commit()

1733  @provide_session
1734  def handle_failure(self, error, test_mode=False, context=None, session=None):
1735  self.log.exception(error)
1736  task = self.task
1737  self.end_date = timezone.utcnow()
1738  self.set_duration()
1739  Stats.incr('operator_failures_{}'.format(task.__class__.__name__), 1, 1)
1740  Stats.incr('ti_failures')
1741  if not test_mode:
1742  session.add(Log(State.FAILED, self))
1743 
1744  # Log failure duration
1745  session.add(TaskFail(task, self.execution_date, self.start_date, self.end_date))
1746 
1747  # Let's go deeper
1748  try:
1749  # Since this function is called only when the TI state is running,
1750  # try_number contains the current try_number (not the next). We
1751  # only mark task instance as FAILED if the next task instance
1752  # try_number exceeds the max_tries.
1753  if self.is_eligible_to_retry():
1754  self.state = State.UP_FOR_RETRY
1755  self.log.info('Marking task as UP_FOR_RETRY')
1756  if task.email_on_retry and task.email:
1757  self.email_alert(error, is_retry=True)
1758  else:
1759  self.state = State.FAILED
1760  if task.retries:
1761  self.log.info('All retries failed; marking task as FAILED')
1762  else:
1763  self.log.info('Marking task as FAILED.')
1764  if task.email_on_failure and task.email:
1765  self.email_alert(error, is_retry=False)
1766  except Exception as e2:
1767  self.log.error('Failed to send email to: %s', task.email)
1768  self.log.exception(e2)
1769 
1770  # Handling callbacks pessimistically
1771  try:
1772  if self.state == State.UP_FOR_RETRY and task.on_retry_callback:
1773  task.on_retry_callback(context)
1774  if self.state == State.FAILED and task.on_failure_callback:
1775  task.on_failure_callback(context)
1776  except Exception as e3:
1777  self.log.error("Failed at executing callback")
1778  self.log.exception(e3)
1779 
1780  if not test_mode:
1781  session.merge(self)
1782  session.commit()
1783 
1784  def is_eligible_to_retry(self):
1785  """Is task instance is eligible for retry"""
1786  return self.task.retries and self.try_number <= self.max_tries

1984  def xcom_pull(
1985  self,
1986  task_ids=None,
1987  dag_id=None,
1988  key=XCOM_RETURN_KEY,
1989  include_prior_dates=False):
1990  """
1991  Pull XComs that optionally meet certain criteria.
1992 
1993  The default value for `key` limits the search to XComs
1994  that were returned by other tasks (as opposed to those that were pushed
1995  manually). To remove this filter, pass key=None (or any desired value).
1996 
1997  If a single task_id string is provided, the result is the value of the
1998  most recent matching XCom from that task_id. If multiple task_ids are
1999  provided, a tuple of matching values is returned. None is returned
2000  whenever no matches are found.
2001 
2002  :param key: A key for the XCom. If provided, only XComs with matching
2003  keys will be returned. The default key is 'return_value', also
2004  available as a constant XCOM_RETURN_KEY. This key is automatically
2005  given to XComs returned by tasks (as opposed to being pushed
2006  manually). To remove the filter, pass key=None.
2007  :type key: string
2008  :param task_ids: Only XComs from tasks with matching ids will be
2009  pulled. Can pass None to remove the filter.
2010  :type task_ids: string or iterable of strings (representing task_ids)
2011  :param dag_id: If provided, only pulls XComs from this DAG.
2012  If None (default), the DAG of the calling task is used.
2013  :type dag_id: string
2014  :param include_prior_dates: If False, only XComs from the current
2015  execution_date are returned. If True, XComs from previous dates
2016  are returned as well.
2017  :type include_prior_dates: bool
2018  """
2019 
2020  if dag_id is None:
2021  dag_id = self.dag_id
2022 
2023  pull_fn = functools.partial(
2024  XCom.get_one,
2025  execution_date=self.execution_date,
2026  key=key,
2027  dag_id=dag_id,
2028  include_prior_dates=include_prior_dates)
2029 
2030  if is_container(task_ids):
2031  return tuple(pull_fn(task_id=t) for t in task_ids)
2032  else:
2033  return pull_fn(task_id=task_ids)

2166 @functools.total_ordering
2167 class BaseOperator(LoggingMixin):
2168  """
2169  Abstract base class for all operators. Since operators create objects that
2170  become nodes in the dag, BaseOperator contains many recursive methods for
2171  dag crawling behavior. To derive this class, you are expected to override
2172  the constructor as well as the 'execute' method.
2173 
2174  Operators derived from this class should perform or trigger certain tasks
2175  synchronously (wait for completion). Example of operators could be an
2176  operator that runs a Pig job (PigOperator), a sensor operator that
2177  waits for a partition to land in Hive (HiveSensorOperator), or one that
2178  moves data from Hive to MySQL (Hive2MySqlOperator). Instances of these
2179  operators (tasks) target specific operations, running specific scripts,
2180  functions or data transfers.
2181 
2182  This class is abstract and shouldn't be instantiated. Instantiating a
2183  class derived from this one results in the creation of a task object,
2184  which ultimately becomes a node in DAG objects. Task dependencies should
2185  be set by using the set_upstream and/or set_downstream methods.
2186 
2187  :param task_id: a unique, meaningful id for the task
2188  :type task_id: string
2189  :param owner: the owner of the task, using the unix username is recommended
2190  :type owner: string
2191  :param retries: the number of retries that should be performed before
2192  failing the task
2193  :type retries: int
2194  :param retry_delay: delay between retries
2195  :type retry_delay: timedelta
2196  :param retry_exponential_backoff: allow progressive longer waits between
2197  retries by using exponential backoff algorithm on retry delay (delay
2198  will be converted into seconds)
2199  :type retry_exponential_backoff: bool
2200  :param max_retry_delay: maximum delay interval between retries
2201  :type max_retry_delay: timedelta
2202  :param start_date: The ``start_date`` for the task, determines
2203  the ``execution_date`` for the first task instance. The best practice
2204  is to have the start_date rounded
2205  to your DAG's ``schedule_interval``. Daily jobs have their start_date
2206  some day at 00:00:00, hourly jobs have their start_date at 00:00
2207  of a specific hour. Note that Airflow simply looks at the latest
2208  ``execution_date`` and adds the ``schedule_interval`` to determine
2209  the next ``execution_date``. It is also very important
2210  to note that different tasks' dependencies
2211  need to line up in time. If task A depends on task B and their
2212  start_date are offset in a way that their execution_date don't line
2213  up, A's dependencies will never be met. If you are looking to delay
2214  a task, for example running a daily task at 2AM, look into the
2215  ``TimeSensor`` and ``TimeDeltaSensor``. We advise against using
2216  dynamic ``start_date`` and recommend using fixed ones. Read the
2217  FAQ entry about start_date for more information.
2218  :type start_date: datetime
2219  :param end_date: if specified, the scheduler won't go beyond this date
2220  :type end_date: datetime
2221  :param depends_on_past: when set to true, task instances will run
2222  sequentially while relying on the previous task's schedule to
2223  succeed. The task instance for the start_date is allowed to run.
2224  :type depends_on_past: bool
2225  :param wait_for_downstream: when set to true, an instance of task
2226  X will wait for tasks immediately downstream of the previous instance
2227  of task X to finish successfully before it runs. This is useful if the
2228  different instances of a task X alter the same asset, and this asset
2229  is used by tasks downstream of task X. Note that depends_on_past
2230  is forced to True wherever wait_for_downstream is used.
2231  :type wait_for_downstream: bool
2232  :param queue: which queue to target when running this job. Not
2233  all executors implement queue management, the CeleryExecutor
2234  does support targeting specific queues.
2235  :type queue: str
2236  :param dag: a reference to the dag the task is attached to (if any)
2237  :type dag: DAG
2238  :param priority_weight: priority weight of this task against other task.
2239  This allows the executor to trigger higher priority tasks before
2240  others when things get backed up.
2241  :type priority_weight: int
2242  :param weight_rule: weighting method used for the effective total
2243  priority weight of the task. Options are:
2244  ``{ downstream | upstream | absolute }`` default is ``downstream``
2245  When set to ``downstream`` the effective weight of the task is the
2246  aggregate sum of all downstream descendants. As a result, upstream
2247  tasks will have higher weight and will be scheduled more aggressively
2248  when using positive weight values. This is useful when you have
2249  multiple dag run instances and desire to have all upstream tasks to
2250  complete for all runs before each dag can continue processing
2251  downstream tasks. When set to ``upstream`` the effective weight is the
2252  aggregate sum of all upstream ancestors. This is the opposite where
2253  downtream tasks have higher weight and will be scheduled more
2254  aggressively when using positive weight values. This is useful when you
2255  have multiple dag run instances and prefer to have each dag complete
2256  before starting upstream tasks of other dags. When set to
2257  ``absolute``, the effective weight is the exact ``priority_weight``
2258  specified without additional weighting. You may want to do this when
2259  you know exactly what priority weight each task should have.
2260  Additionally, when set to ``absolute``, there is bonus effect of
2261  significantly speeding up the task creation process as for very large
2262  DAGS. Options can be set as string or using the constants defined in
2263  the static class ``airflow.utils.WeightRule``
2264  :type weight_rule: str
2265  :param pool: the slot pool this task should run in, slot pools are a
2266  way to limit concurrency for certain tasks
2267  :type pool: str
2268  :param sla: time by which the job is expected to succeed. Note that
2269  this represents the ``timedelta`` after the period is closed. For
2270  example if you set an SLA of 1 hour, the scheduler would send an email
2271  soon after 1:00AM on the ``2016-01-02`` if the ``2016-01-01`` instance
2272  has not succeeded yet.
2273  The scheduler pays special attention for jobs with an SLA and
2274  sends alert
2275  emails for sla misses. SLA misses are also recorded in the database
2276  for future reference. All tasks that share the same SLA time
2277  get bundled in a single email, sent soon after that time. SLA
2278  notification are sent once and only once for each task instance.
2279  :type sla: datetime.timedelta
2280  :param execution_timeout: max time allowed for the execution of
2281  this task instance, if it goes beyond it will raise and fail.
2282  :type execution_timeout: datetime.timedelta
2283  :param on_failure_callback: a function to be called when a task instance
2284  of this task fails. a context dictionary is passed as a single
2285  parameter to this function. Context contains references to related
2286  objects to the task instance and is documented under the macros
2287  section of the API.
2288  :type on_failure_callback: callable
2289  :param on_retry_callback: much like the ``on_failure_callback`` except
2290  that it is executed when retries occur.
2291  :param on_success_callback: much like the ``on_failure_callback`` except
2292  that it is executed when the task succeeds.
2293  :type on_success_callback: callable
2294  :param trigger_rule: defines the rule by which dependencies are applied
2295  for the task to get triggered. Options are:
2296  ``{ all_success | all_failed | all_done | one_success |
2297  one_failed | dummy}``
2298  default is ``all_success``. Options can be set as string or
2299  using the constants defined in the static class
2300  ``airflow.utils.TriggerRule``
2301  :type trigger_rule: str
2302  :param resources: A map of resource parameter names (the argument names of the
2303  Resources constructor) to their values.
2304  :type resources: dict
2305  :param run_as_user: unix username to impersonate while running the task
2306  :type run_as_user: str
2307  :param task_concurrency: When set, a task will be able to limit the concurrent
2308  runs across execution_dates
2309  :type task_concurrency: int
2310  :param executor_config: Additional task-level configuration parameters that are
2311  interpreted by a specific executor. Parameters are namespaced by the name of
2312  executor.
2313  ``example: to run this task in a specific docker container through
2314  the KubernetesExecutor
2315  MyOperator(...,
2316  executor_config={
2317  "KubernetesExecutor":
2318  {"image": "myCustomDockerImage"}
2319  }

2512  hash_components = [type(self)]
2513  for c in self._comps:
2514  val = getattr(self, c, None)
2515  try:
2516  hash(val)
2517  hash_components.append(val)

2524  def __rshift__(self, other):
2525  """
2526  Implements Self >> Other == self.set_downstream(other)
2527 
2528  If "Other" is a DAG, the DAG is assigned to the Operator.
2529  """
2530  if isinstance(other, DAG):
2531  # if this dag is already assigned, do nothing
2532  # otherwise, do normal dag assignment
2533  if not (self.has_dag() and self.dag is other):
2534  self.dag = other
2535  else:
2536  self.set_downstream(other)
2537  return other
2538 
2539  def __lshift__(self, other):
2540  """
2541  Implements Self << Other == self.set_upstream(other)
2542 
2543  If "Other" is a DAG, the DAG is assigned to the Operator.
2544  """
2545  if isinstance(other, DAG):
2546  # if this dag is already assigned, do nothing
2547  # otherwise, do normal dag assignment
2548  if not (self.has_dag() and self.dag is other):
2549  self.dag = other
2550  else:
2551  self.set_upstream(other)
2552  return other
2553 
2554  def __rrshift__(self, other):
2555  """
2556  Called for [DAG] >> [Operator] because DAGs don't have
2557  __rshift__ operators.
2558  """
2559  self.__lshift__(other)
2560  return self
2561 
2562  def __rlshift__(self, other):
2563  """
2564  Called for [DAG] << [Operator] because DAGs don't have
2565  __lshift__ operators.
2566  """
2567  self.__rshift__(other)
2568  return self

2721  def render_template_from_field(self, attr, content, context, jinja_env):
2722  """
2723  Renders a template from a field. If the field is a string, it will
2724  simply render the string and return the result. If it is a collection or
2725  nested set of collections, it will traverse the structure and render
2726  all strings in it.
2727  """
2728  rt = self.render_template
2729  if isinstance(content, six.string_types):
2730  result = jinja_env.from_string(content).render(**context)
2731  elif isinstance(content, (list, tuple)):
2732  result = [rt(attr, e, context) for e in content]
2733  elif isinstance(content, numbers.Number):
2734  result = content
2735  elif isinstance(content, dict):
2736  result = {
2737  k: rt("{}[{}]".format(attr, k), v, context)
2738  for k, v in list(content.items())}
2739  else:
2740  param_type = type(content)
2741  msg = (
2742  "Type '{param_type}' used for parameter '{attr}' is "
2743  "not supported for templating").format(**locals())
2744  raise AirflowException(msg)
2745  return result

2747  def render_template(self, attr, content, context):
2748  """
2749  Renders a template either from a file or directly in a field, and returns
2750  the rendered result.
2751  """
2752  jinja_env = self.dag.get_template_env() \
2753  if hasattr(self, 'dag') \
2754  else jinja2.Environment(cache_size=0)
2755 
2756  exts = self.__class__.template_ext
2757  if (
2758  isinstance(content, six.string_types) and
2759  any([content.endswith(ext) for ext in exts])):
2760  return jinja_env.get_template(content).render(**context)
2761  else:
2762  return self.render_template_from_field(attr, content, context, jinja_env)

2808  end_date=None,
2809  upstream=False,
2810  downstream=False,
2811  session=None):

2813  Clears the state of task instances associated with the task, following

2819  if start_date:
2820  qry = qry.filter(TI.execution_date >= start_date)
2821  if end_date:

2829

2835 
2836  count = qry.count()
2837 
2838  clear_task_instances(qry.all(), session, dag=self.dag)

2841

2947  def _set_relatives(self, task_or_task_list, upstream=False):
2948  try:
2949  task_list = list(task_or_task_list)
2950  except TypeError:
2951  task_list = [task_or_task_list]
2952 
2953  for t in task_list:
2954  if not isinstance(t, BaseOperator):
2955  raise AirflowException(
2956  "Relationships can only be set between "
2957  "Operators; received {}".format(t.__class__.__name__))
2958 
2959  # relationships can only be set if the tasks share a single DAG. Tasks
2960  # without a DAG are assigned to that DAG.
2961  dags = {t._dag.dag_id: t._dag for t in [self] + task_list if t.has_dag()}
2962 
2963  if len(dags) > 1:
2964  raise AirflowException(
2965  'Tried to set relationships between tasks in '
2966  'more than one DAG: {}'.format(dags.values()))
2967  elif len(dags) == 1:
2968  dag = dags.popitem()[1]
2969  else:
2970  raise AirflowException(
2971  "Tried to create relationships between tasks that don't have "
2972  "DAGs yet. Set the DAG for at least one "
2973  "task and try again: {}".format([self] + task_list))
2974 
2975  if dag and not self.has_dag():
2976  self.dag = dag
2977 
2978  for task in task_list:
2979  if dag and not task.has_dag():
2980  task.dag = dag
2981  if upstream:
2982  task.add_only_new(task._downstream_task_ids, self.task_id)
2983  self.add_only_new(self._upstream_task_ids, task.task_id)
2984  else:
2985  self.add_only_new(self._downstream_task_ids, task.task_id)
2986  task.add_only_new(task._upstream_task_ids, self.task_id)

3075 @functools.total_ordering
3076 class DAG(BaseDag, LoggingMixin):
3077  """
3078  A dag (directed acyclic graph) is a collection of tasks with directional
3079  dependencies. A dag also has a schedule, a start end an end date
3080  (optional). For each schedule, (say daily or hourly), the DAG needs to run
3081  each individual tasks as their dependencies are met. Certain tasks have
3082  the property of depending on their own past, meaning that they can't run
3083  until their previous schedule (and upstream tasks) are completed.
3084 
3085  DAGs essentially act as namespaces for tasks. A task_id can only be
3086  added once to a DAG.
3087 
3088  :param dag_id: The id of the DAG
3089  :type dag_id: string
3090  :param description: The description for the DAG to e.g. be shown on the webserver
3091  :type description: string
3092  :param schedule_interval: Defines how often that DAG runs, this
3093  timedelta object gets added to your latest task instance's
3094  execution_date to figure out the next schedule
3095  :type schedule_interval: datetime.timedelta or
3096  dateutil.relativedelta.relativedelta or str that acts as a cron
3097  expression
3098  :param start_date: The timestamp from which the scheduler will
3099  attempt to backfill
3100  :type start_date: datetime.datetime
3101  :param end_date: A date beyond which your DAG won't run, leave to None
3102  for open ended scheduling
3103  :type end_date: datetime.datetime
3104  :param template_searchpath: This list of folders (non relative)
3105  defines where jinja will look for your templates. Order matters.
3106  Note that jinja/airflow includes the path of your DAG file by
3107  default
3108  :type template_searchpath: string or list of stings
3109  :param user_defined_macros: a dictionary of macros that will be exposed
3110  in your jinja templates. For example, passing ``dict(foo='bar')``
3111  to this argument allows you to ``{{ foo }}`` in all jinja
3112  templates related to this DAG. Note that you can pass any
3113  type of object here.
3114  :type user_defined_macros: dict
3115  :param user_defined_filters: a dictionary of filters that will be exposed
3116  in your jinja templates. For example, passing
3117  ``dict(hello=lambda name: 'Hello %s' % name)`` to this argument allows
3118  you to ``{{ 'world' | hello }}`` in all jinja templates related to
3119  this DAG.
3120  :type user_defined_filters: dict
3121  :param default_args: A dictionary of default parameters to be used
3122  as constructor keyword parameters when initialising operators.
3123  Note that operators have the same hook, and precede those defined
3124  here, meaning that if your dict contains `'depends_on_past': True`
3125  here and `'depends_on_past': False` in the operator's call
3126  `default_args`, the actual value will be `False`.
3127  :type default_args: dict
3128  :param params: a dictionary of DAG level parameters that are made
3129  accessible in templates, namespaced under `params`. These
3130  params can be overridden at the task level.
3131  :type params: dict
3132  :param concurrency: the number of task instances allowed to run
3133  concurrently
3134  :type concurrency: int
3135  :param max_active_runs: maximum number of active DAG runs, beyond this
3136  number of DAG runs in a running state, the scheduler won't create
3137  new active DAG runs

3348  def get_run_dates(self, start_date, end_date=None):

3352

3354  :type start_date: datetime

3356  :type end_date: datetime

3677  def topological_sort(self):
3678  """
3679  Sorts tasks in topographical order, such that a task comes after any of its
3680  upstream dependencies.
3681 
3682  Heavily inspired by:
3683  http://blog.jupo.org/2012/04/06/topological-sorting-acyclic-directed-graphs/
3684 
3685  :return: list of tasks in topological order
3686  """
3687 
3688  # copy the the tasks so we leave it unmodified
3689  graph_unsorted = self.tasks[:]
3690 
3691  graph_sorted = []
3692 
3693  # special case
3694  if len(self.tasks) == 0:
3695  return tuple(graph_sorted)
3696 
3697  # Run until the unsorted graph is empty.
3698  while graph_unsorted:
3699  # Go through each of the node/edges pairs in the unsorted
3700  # graph. If a set of edges doesn't contain any nodes that
3701  # haven't been resolved, that is, that are still in the
3702  # unsorted graph, remove the pair from the unsorted graph,
3703  # and append it to the sorted graph. Note here that by using
3704  # using the items() method for iterating, a copy of the
3705  # unsorted graph is used, allowing us to modify the unsorted
3706  # graph as we move through it. We also keep a flag for
3707  # checking that that graph is acyclic, which is true if any
3708  # nodes are resolved during each pass through the graph. If
3709  # not, we need to bail out as the graph therefore can't be
3710  # sorted.
3711  acyclic = False
3712  for node in list(graph_unsorted):
3713  for edge in node.upstream_list:
3714  if edge in graph_unsorted:
3715  break
3716  # no edges in upstream tasks
3717  else:
3718  acyclic = True
3719  graph_unsorted.remove(node)
3720  graph_sorted.append(node)
3721 
3722  if not acyclic:
3723  raise AirflowException("A cyclic dependency occurred in dag: {}"
3724  .format(self.dag_id))
3725 
3726  return tuple(graph_sorted)

3879  def __deepcopy__(self, memo):
3880  # Swiwtcharoo to go around deepcopying objects coming through the
3881  # backdoor
3882  cls = self.__class__
3883  result = cls.__new__(cls)
3884  memo[id(self)] = result
3885  for k, v in list(self.__dict__.items()):
3886  if k not in ('user_defined_macros', 'user_defined_filters', 'params'):
3887  setattr(result, k, copy.deepcopy(v, memo))
3888 
3889  result.user_defined_macros = self.user_defined_macros
3890  result.user_defined_filters = self.user_defined_filters
3891  result.params = self.params
3892  return result

3894  def sub_dag(self, task_regex, include_downstream=False,
3895  include_upstream=True):
3896  """
3897  Returns a subset of the current dag as a deep copy of the current dag
3898  based on a regex that should match one or many tasks, and includes
3899  upstream and downstream neighbours based on the flag passed.
3900  """
3901 
3902  dag = copy.deepcopy(self)
3903 
3904  regex_match = [
3905  t for t in dag.tasks if re.findall(task_regex, t.task_id)]
3906  also_include = []
3907  for t in regex_match:
3908  if include_downstream:
3909  also_include += t.get_flat_relatives(upstream=False)
3910  if include_upstream:
3911  also_include += t.get_flat_relatives(upstream=True)
3912 
3913  # Compiling the unique list of tasks that made the cut
3914  dag.task_dict = {t.task_id: t for t in regex_match + also_include}
3915  for t in dag.tasks:
3916  # Removing upstream/downstream references to tasks that did not
3917  # made the cut
3918  t._upstream_task_ids = t._upstream_task_ids.intersection(dag.task_dict.keys())
3919  t._downstream_task_ids = t._downstream_task_ids.intersection(
3920  dag.task_dict.keys())
3921 
3922  if len(dag.tasks) < len(self.tasks):
3923  dag.partial = True
3924 
3925  return dag

3980  def add_task(self, task):
3981  """
3982  Add a task to the DAG
3983 
3984  :param task: the task you want to add
3985  :type task: task
3986  """
3987  if not self.start_date and not task.start_date:
3988  raise AirflowException("Task is missing the start_date parameter")
3989  # if the task has no start date, assign it the same as the DAG
3990  elif not task.start_date:
3991  task.start_date = self.start_date
3992  # otherwise, the task will start on the later of its own start date and
3993  # the DAG's start date
3994  elif self.start_date:
3995  task.start_date = max(task.start_date, self.start_date)
3996 
3997  # if the task has no end date, assign it the same as the dag
3998  if not task.end_date:
3999  task.end_date = self.end_date
4000  # otherwise, the task will end on the earlier of its own end date and
4001  # the DAG's end date
4002  elif task.end_date and self.end_date:
4003  task.end_date = min(task.end_date, self.end_date)
4004 
4005  if task.task_id in self.task_dict:
4006  # TODO: raise an error in Airflow 2.0
4007  warnings.warn(
4008  'The requested task could not be added to the DAG because a '
4009  'task with task_id {} is already in the DAG. Starting in '
4010  'Airflow 2.0, trying to overwrite a task will raise an '
4011  'exception.'.format(task.task_id),
4012  category=PendingDeprecationWarning)
4013  else:
4014  self.task_dict[task.task_id] = task
4015  task.dag = self
4016 
4017  self.task_count = len(self.task_dict)

4273  def test_cycle(self):
4274  """
4275  Check to see if there are any cycles in the DAG. Returns False if no cycle found,
4276  otherwise raises exception.
4277  """
4278 
4279  # default of int is 0 which corresponds to CYCLE_NEW
4280  visit_map = defaultdict(int)
4281  for task_id in self.task_dict.keys():
4282  # print('starting %s' % task_id)
4283  if visit_map[task_id] == DagBag.CYCLE_NEW:
4284  self._test_cycle_helper(visit_map, task_id)
4285  return False
4286 
4287  def _test_cycle_helper(self, visit_map, task_id):
4288  """
4289  Checks if a cycle exists from the input task using DFS traversal
4290  """
4291 
4292  # print('Inspecting %s' % task_id)
4293  if visit_map[task_id] == DagBag.CYCLE_DONE:
4294  return False
4295 
4296  visit_map[task_id] = DagBag.CYCLE_IN_PROGRESS
4297 
4298  task = self.task_dict[task_id]
4299  for descendant_id in task.get_direct_relative_ids():
4300  if visit_map[descendant_id] == DagBag.CYCLE_IN_PROGRESS:
4301  msg = "Cycle detected in DAG. Faulty task: {0} to {1}".format(
4302  task_id, descendant_id)
4303  raise AirflowDagCycleException(msg)
4304  else:
4305  self._test_cycle_helper(visit_map, descendant_id)
4306 
4307  visit_map[task_id] = DagBag.CYCLE_DONE

4975  @provide_session
4976  def update_state(self, session=None):
4977  """
4978  Determines the overall state of the DagRun based on the state
4979  of its TaskInstances.
4980 
4981  :return: State
4982  """
4983 
4984  dag = self.get_dag()
4985 
4986  tis = self.get_task_instances(session=session)
4987 
4988  self.log.debug("Updating state for %s considering %s task(s)", self, len(tis))
4989 
4990  for ti in list(tis):
4991  # skip in db?
4992  if ti.state == State.REMOVED:
4993  tis.remove(ti)
4994  else:
4995  ti.task = dag.get_task(ti.task_id)
4996 
4997  # pre-calculate
4998  # db is faster
4999  start_dttm = timezone.utcnow()
5000  unfinished_tasks = self.get_task_instances(
5001  state=State.unfinished(),
5002  session=session
5003  )
5004  none_depends_on_past = all(not t.task.depends_on_past for t in unfinished_tasks)
5005  none_task_concurrency = all(t.task.task_concurrency is None
5006  for t in unfinished_tasks)
5007  # small speed up
5008  if unfinished_tasks and none_depends_on_past and none_task_concurrency:
5009  # todo: this can actually get pretty slow: one task costs between 0.01-015s
5010  no_dependencies_met = True
5011  for ut in unfinished_tasks:
5012  # We need to flag upstream and check for changes because upstream
5013  # failures can result in deadlock false positives
5014  old_state = ut.state
5015  deps_met = ut.are_dependencies_met(
5016  dep_context=DepContext(
5017  flag_upstream_failed=True,
5018  ignore_in_retry_period=True),
5019  session=session)
5020  if deps_met or old_state != ut.current_state(session=session):
5021  no_dependencies_met = False
5022  break
5023 
5024  duration = (timezone.utcnow() - start_dttm).total_seconds() * 1000
5025  Stats.timing("dagrun.dependency-check.{}".format(self.dag_id), duration)
5026 
5027  # future: remove the check on adhoc tasks (=active_tasks)
5028  if len(tis) == len(dag.active_tasks):
5029  root_ids = [t.task_id for t in dag.roots]
5030  roots = [t for t in tis if t.task_id in root_ids]
5031 
5032  # if all roots finished and at least one failed, the run failed
5033  if (not unfinished_tasks and
5034  any(r.state in (State.FAILED, State.UPSTREAM_FAILED) for r in roots)):
5035  self.log.info('Marking run %s failed', self)
5036  self.state = State.FAILED
5037  dag.handle_callback(self, success=False, reason='task_failure',
5038  session=session)
5039 
5040  # if all roots succeeded and no unfinished tasks, the run succeeded
5041  elif not unfinished_tasks and all(r.state in (State.SUCCESS, State.SKIPPED)
5042  for r in roots):
5043  self.log.info('Marking run %s successful', self)
5044  self.state = State.SUCCESS
5045  dag.handle_callback(self, success=True, reason='success', session=session)
5046 
5047  # if *all tasks* are deadlocked, the run failed
5048  elif (unfinished_tasks and none_depends_on_past and
5049  none_task_concurrency and no_dependencies_met):
5050  self.log.info('Deadlock; marking run %s failed', self)
5051  self.state = State.FAILED
5052  dag.handle_callback(self, success=False, reason='all_tasks_deadlocked',
5053  session=session)
5054 
5055  # finally, if the roots aren't done, the dag is still running
5056  else:
5057  self.state = State.RUNNING
5058 
5059  # todo: determine we want to use with_for_update to make sure to lock the run
5060  session.merge(self)
5061  session.commit()
5062 
5063  return self.state
5064 
5065  @provide_session
5066  def verify_integrity(self, session=None):
5067  """
5068  Verifies the DagRun by checking for removed tasks or tasks that are not in the
5069  database yet. It will set state to removed or add the task if required.
5070  """
5071  dag = self.get_dag()
5072  tis = self.get_task_instances(session=session)
5073 
5074  # check for removed or restored tasks
5075  task_ids = []
5076  for ti in tis:
5077  task_ids.append(ti.task_id)
5078  task = None
5079  try:
5080  task = dag.get_task(ti.task_id)
5081  except AirflowException:
5082  if ti.state == State.REMOVED:
5083  pass # ti has already been removed, just ignore it
5084  elif self.state is not State.RUNNING and not dag.partial:
5085  self.log.warning("Failed to get task '{}' for dag '{}'. "
5086  "Marking it as removed.".format(ti, dag))
5087  Stats.incr(
5088  "task_removed_from_dag.{}".format(dag.dag_id), 1, 1)
5089  ti.state = State.REMOVED
5090 
5091  is_task_in_dag = task is not None
5092  should_restore_task = is_task_in_dag and ti.state == State.REMOVED
5093  if should_restore_task:
5094  self.log.info("Restoring task '{}' which was previously "
5095  "removed from DAG '{}'".format(ti, dag))
5096  Stats.incr("task_restored_to_dag.{}".format(dag.dag_id), 1, 1)
5097  ti.state = State.NONE
5098 
5099  # check for missing tasks
5100  for task in six.itervalues(dag.task_dict):
5101  if task.adhoc:
5102  continue
5103 
5104  if task.task_id not in task_ids:
5105  ti = TaskInstance(task, self.execution_date)
5106  session.add(ti)
5107 
5108  session.commit()
5109 
5110  @staticmethod
5111  def get_run(session, dag_id, execution_date):
5112  """
5113  :param dag_id: DAG ID
5114  :type dag_id: unicode
5115  :param execution_date: execution date
5116  :type execution_date: datetime
5117  :return: DagRun corresponding to the given dag_id and execution date
5118  if one exists. None otherwise.
5119  :rtype: DagRun
5120  """
5121  qry = session.query(DagRun).filter(
5122  DagRun.dag_id == dag_id,
5123  DagRun.external_trigger == False, # noqa
5124  DagRun.execution_date == execution_date,
5125  )
5126  return qry.first()
5127 
5128  @property
5129  def is_backfill(self):
5130  from airflow.jobs import BackfillJob
5131  return self.run_id.startswith(BackfillJob.ID_PREFIX)
5132 
5133  @classmethod
5134  @provide_session
5135  def get_latest_runs(cls, session):
5136  """Returns the latest DagRun for each DAG. """
5137  subquery = (
5138  session
5139  .query(
5140  cls.dag_id,
5141  func.max(cls.execution_date).label('execution_date'))
5142  .group_by(cls.dag_id)
5143  .subquery()
5144  )
5145  dagruns = (
5146  session
5147  .query(cls)
5148  .join(subquery,
5149  and_(cls.dag_id == subquery.c.dag_id,
5150  cls.execution_date == subquery.c.execution_date))
5151  .all()
5152  )
5153  return dagruns
